Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

[This report goes more thoroughly into the background of the 4 drugs tested in the clinical trial.

Community trust still remains a serious barrier to success. Will the community accept the safety and need for early treatment with these therapeutics? And with termination of the clinical trial where the treatment was free of charge, what will the cost be to the patient, and can they afford it? So while this news is indeed exciting, the drugs alone are not going to be a cure all until the community is on board with it.

As stated in the report cited above, challenges remain daunting. "I think the news today is fantastic. It gives us a new tool in our toolbox against Ebola," says Mike Ryan, executive director of WHO's Health Emergencies Programme. "But it doesn't stop Ebola. What will stop Ebola, under professor Muyembe's leadership and that of the government of the DRC, is good surveillance, good infection prevention and control, good community engagement, excellent vaccinations, and the use of these therapeutics in the most effective way possible." - Mod.LK]

